### Update rules

In addition to the four ways of approximating the expected Hessian (summarized in Table 1), we also consider four variants of bong, based on what kind of loss we optimize and what kind of update we perform, as we describe below. See Table 2 for a summary.

**bong** (Bayesian online natural gradient) performs one step of NGD on the expected log-likelihood. We set learning rate to \(\alpha_{t}=1\) since this is optimal for conjugate models. The update (for an exponential variational family) is as in Eq. (5):

\[\bm{\psi}_{t}=\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}+\nabla_{\bm{\rho}_{|t-1}}\mathbb{E}_{\bm{ \theta}_{t}\sim q_{\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}}}[\log p(\bm{y}_{t}|\bm{x}_{t},\bm{\theta }_{t})]\] (30)

**bog** (Bayesian online gradient) performs one step of GD (instead of NGD) on the expected log-likelihood. We include a learning rate \(\alpha\) because GD does not have the scale-invariance of NGD:

\[\bm{\psi}_{t}=\bm{\psi}_{t}+\alpha_{t}\nabla_{\bm{\psi}_{t}}\mathbb{E}_{\bm{ \theta}_{t}\sim q_{\bm{\psi}_{t}}}[\log p(\bm{y}_{t}|f_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t}))]\] (31)

**blr** (Bayesian learning rule, (Khan and Rue, 2023)) uses NGD (like bong) but optimizes the VI loss using multiple iterations, instead of optimizing the expected NLL with a single step. When modified to the online setting, blr starts an inner loop at each time step with \(\bm{\psi}_{t,0}=\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}\) and iterates

\[\bm{\psi}_{t,i}=\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}+\alpha_{t}\mathbf{F}_{\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}} \nabla_{\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}}\Big{(}\mathbb{E}_{\bm{\theta}_{t}\sim q_{\bm{\psi}_ {t,i-1}}}[\log p(\bm{y}_{t}|f_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t}))]-D_{\mathbb{KL}}\big{(}q_{ \bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}}|q_{\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}}\big{)}\Big{)}\] (32)

For an exponential variational family this can be written in mirror descent form

\[\bm{\psi}_{t,i}=\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}+\alpha_{t}\nabla_{\bm{\rho}_{t,i-1}}\Big{(} \mathbb{E}_{\bm{\theta}_{t}\sim q_{\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}}}[\log p(\bm{y}_{t}|f_{t}( \bm{\theta}_{t}))]-D_{\mathbb{KL}}\big{(}q_{\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}}|q_{\bm{\psi}_{t| t-1}}\big{)}\Big{)}\] (33)

**bbb** (Bayes By Backprop, (Blundell et al., 2015)) is like blr but uses GD instead of NGD. When adapted to online learning, it starts each time step at \(\bm{\psi}_{t,0}=\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}\) and iterates with GD:

\[\bm{\psi}_{t,i}=\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}+\alpha_{t}\nabla_{\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}}\Big{(} \mathbb{E}_{\bm{\theta}_{t}\sim q_{\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}}}[\log p(\bm{y}_{t}|f_{t}( \bm{\theta}_{t}))]-D_{\mathbb{KL}}\big{(}q_{\bm{\psi}_{t,i-1}}|q_{\bm{\psi}_{t |t-1}}\big{)}\Big{)}\] (34)

