## Appendix D Mirror descent formulation

In this section we give a more detailed derivation of bong as mirror descent and use this to give two alternative interpretations of how bong approximates exact VB: (1) by approximating the expected NLL as linear in the expectation parameter \(\bm{\rho}\), or (2) by replacing an implicit update with an explicit one.

Assume the variational family is an exponential one as introduced at the end of Section 3, with natural and dual parameters \(\bm{\psi}\) and \(\bm{\rho}\), sufficient statistics \(T(\bm{\theta})\), and log-partition \(\Phi(\bm{\psi})\):

\[q_{\bm{\psi}}(\bm{\theta}) =\exp\left(\bm{\psi}^{\intercal}T(\bm{\theta})-\Phi(\bm{\psi})\right)\] (59) \[\bm{\rho} =\mathbb{E}_{\bm{\theta}\sim q_{\bm{\psi}}}[T(\bm{\theta})]\] (60)We first review how NGD on an exponential family is a special case of mirror descent (Khan and Rue, 2023; Martens, 2020). The mirror map is the gradient of the log-partition, which satisfies the thermodynamic identity

\[\bm{\rho}=\nabla\Phi(\bm{\psi})\] (61)

This is a bijection when \(\Phi\) is convex (which includes the cases we study), so we can implicitly treat \(\bm{\psi}\) and \(\bm{\rho}\) as functions of each other. Given a loss function \(L(\bm{\psi})\), MD iteratively solves the local optimization problem

\[\bm{\psi}_{i+1}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{\psi}}\left\langle\nabla_{\bm{ \rho}_{i}}L(\bm{\psi}_{i}),\bm{\rho}\right\rangle+\frac{1}{\alpha}\mathbb{D}_ {\Phi}(\bm{\psi}_{i},\bm{\psi})\] (62)

The first term is a linear (in \(\bm{\rho}\)) approximation of \(L\) about the previous iteration \(\bm{\psi}_{i}\) and the second term is the Bregman divergence

\[\mathbb{D}_{\Phi}(\bm{\psi}_{i},\bm{\psi}_{i+1})=\Phi(\bm{\psi}_{i})-\Phi(\bm {\psi}_{i+1})-(\bm{\psi}_{i}-\bm{\psi}_{i+1})^{\mathsf{T}}\,\bm{\rho}_{i+1}\] (63)

The Bregman divergence acts as a regularizer toward \(\bm{\psi}_{i}\) and captures the intrinsic geometry of the parameter space because of its equivalence with the (reverse) KL divergence

\[D_{\mathrm{KL}}\big{(}q_{\bm{\psi}_{i+1}}|\bm{\psi}_{\bm{\psi}_{ i}}\big{)} =\mathbb{E}_{\bm{\theta}\sim q_{\bm{\psi}_{i+1}}}[(\bm{\psi}_{i+1 }-\bm{\psi}_{i})^{\mathsf{T}}\,T(\bm{\theta})+\Phi(\bm{\psi}_{i})-\Phi(\bm{ \psi}_{i+1})]\] (64) \[=\mathbb{D}_{\Phi}(\bm{\psi}_{i},\bm{\psi}_{i+1})\] (65)

Importantly, this recursive regularizer is not part of the loss and serves only to define an iterated algorithm that converges to a local minimum of \(L\). Solving Eq. (62) by differentiating by \(\bm{\rho}\) yields the MD update

\[\bm{\psi}_{i+1}=\bm{\psi}_{i}-\alpha\nabla_{\bm{\rho}_{i}}L(\bm{\psi}_{i})\] (66)

Because the Fisher matrix for an exponential family is \(\mathbf{F}_{\bm{\psi}}=\partial\bm{\rho}/\partial\bm{\psi}\), this is equivalent to NGD with respect to \(\bm{\psi}\). Khan and Rue (2023) offer this as a derivation of the BLR, when \(L(\bm{\psi})\) is taken to be the variational loss from Eq. (1).

By applying this analysis to the online setting, our approach can be seen to follow from two insights. First, the online variational loss in Eq. (2) already includes KL divergence from the previous step, so we do not need the artificial regularizer in Eq. (62). That is, if we start from the online variational problem in Eq. (4) and define \(L_{t}(\bm{\psi})\) as the expected NLL,

\[L_{t}(\bm{\psi})=-\mathbb{E}_{\bm{\theta}_{t}\sim q_{\bm{\psi}}}[\log p(\bm{y }_{t}|f_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t}))]\] (67)

then replacing \(L_{t}(\bm{\psi})\) with a linear approximation based at \(\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}\) and applying Eq. (65) leads to

\[\bm{\psi}_{t}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{\psi}}\left\langle\nabla_{\bm{ \rho}_{t|t-1}}L_{t}(\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}),\bm{\rho}\right\rangle+\mathbb{D}_{ \Phi}(\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1},\bm{\psi})\] (68)

By comparing to Eq. (62) we see this defines an MD algorithm with unit learning rate that works in a single step rather than by iterating. Paralleling the derivation of Eq. (66) from Eq. (62) we get

\[\bm{\psi}_{t}=\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}-\nabla_{\bm{\rho}_{t|t-1}}L_{t}(\bm{\psi}_{t| t-1})\] (69)

which matches the bong update in Eq. (5). Thus bong can be seen as an approximate solution of the online variational problem in Eq. (4) based on linearizing the expected NLL wrt \(\bm{\rho}\). (Note this is different from the assumption underlying bong-lin that \(f_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t})\) or \(h_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t})\) is linear in \(\bm{\theta}_{t}\).)

Second, in the conjugate case, this linearity assumption is true: \(L_{t}\) is linear in \(\bm{\rho}\) (see proof of Proposition 4.1). Therefore 68 is equivalent to solving Eq. (4) exactly:

\[\bm{\psi}_{t}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\bm{\psi}}L_{t}(\bm{\psi})+\mathbb{D}_ {\Phi}(\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1},\bm{\psi})\] (70)

This recapitulates Proposition 4.1 that bong is Bayes optimal in the conjugate case. In general the exact solution to Eq. (70) is

\[\bm{\psi}_{t}=\bm{\psi}_{t|t-1}-\nabla_{\bm{\rho}_{t}}L_{t}(\bm{\psi}_{t})\] (71)

This is an implicit update because the gradient is evaluated at the (unknown) posterior, whereas Eq. (69) is an explicit update because it evaluates the gradient at the prior. (In the Gaussian case these can be shown to match the implicit and explicit RVGA updates of (Lambert et al., 2021).) Therefore bong can be also interpreted as an approximation of exact VB that replaces the implicit update, Eq. (71), with an explicit update, Eq. (69).

